WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:40.000 --> 00:42.001
Down, please.

00:54.527 --> 00:56.008
Oh, it's such a shame.

00:56.248 --> 00:59.239
All those toys stored away,
nobody to play with them.

00:59.290 --> 01:02.201
Anti-German feeling is running high,
Miss Calthorpe.

01:02.251 --> 01:06.803
It's store policy not to stock
anything German. Too old to play
with dolls, aren't you?

01:06.853 --> 01:11.885
It's not me I'm thinking of,
it's my sister Ruth. She doesn't have
many toys. Morning, Franco.

01:11.935 --> 01:15.327
Morning, Grace.
Seven, eight...

01:15.377 --> 01:18.169
The Rimmel mascara is
becoming popular, Jessie.

01:18.218 --> 01:20.220
I want to push it.
Yes, Miss Hawkins.

01:24.342 --> 01:28.774
I thought about going down
to Greenwich this weekend,
see the boats, have a meal.

01:28.823 --> 01:33.977
Would you like to come? I can't this
weekend. The next one, then?

01:34.027 --> 01:36.898
Do you not want to come with me?

01:36.947 --> 01:39.660
My father says
I mustn't go out with foreign boys.

01:39.709 --> 01:42.511
I'm really sorry, Franco,
but that's the way it is.

01:55.557 --> 01:58.279
Good morning, Miss Towler.
Morning, Mr Leclair.

02:07.083 --> 02:12.315
Look, Frank, the American government
shouldn't be trading with both
Germany and Britain.

02:12.365 --> 02:14.366
They're profiting from war.

02:15.126 --> 02:17.447
Can I quote you on that?
You certainly can.

02:19.569 --> 02:21.890
Good morning, Mr Edwards.
Mrs Selfridge.

02:23.610 --> 02:27.563
I'll write this up for tomorrow.
I appreciate it. Thanks, Frank.

02:27.613 --> 02:30.765
What's the matter?
Everyone's leaving London.

02:30.814 --> 02:32.805
Oh. Who's gone now?

02:32.855 --> 02:37.487
Hetty Madderson. Oh.
"Dear Rose, so sorry not to be able
to come to dine next week."

02:37.537 --> 02:42.820
Apparently the boats are crammed
with Americans. Don't they care how
bad it looks? Seems not.

02:46.062 --> 02:49.614
Good morning. Morning, Mr Selfridge.
Good morning, Mr Selfridge.

02:49.664 --> 02:52.695
Good morning. Good morning,
Mr Selfridge. Good morning.

02:52.745 --> 02:54.736
This is looking splendid.

02:54.786 --> 02:57.628
Pride in your department,
this is what I like to see.

02:59.068 --> 03:02.460
It's funny. Most of the time
I forget who you are.

03:02.510 --> 03:04.630
I mean, I think you're normal,
like me.

03:06.111 --> 03:09.424
I am normal.
You're Gordon Selfridge.

03:09.474 --> 03:11.474
You couldn't be normal if you tried.

03:15.676 --> 03:17.677
Good morning, sir.
Morning.

03:18.758 --> 03:20.878
Good morning, Mr Selfridge.
Morning.

03:21.920 --> 03:25.481
The heads of department are
waiting for you, Mr Selfridge.

03:27.923 --> 03:31.073
I wanna talk to you this morning
about stock. As you know,

03:31.124 --> 03:36.437
we've cleared German goods off
the shelves and replaced them as much
as we can with British goods.

03:36.486 --> 03:41.479
Some of you have done tremendously
well. Miss Hawkins, for example.
Thank you, Mr Selfridge.

03:41.529 --> 03:46.401
I'm pleased to say that Yardley
and Penhaligon's perfume are up
50 percent on last month.

03:46.451 --> 03:50.964
It's about encouraging the clients
to embrace new merchandise.

03:51.014 --> 03:53.855
Once they've tried something
they usually like it.

03:55.656 --> 03:59.247
Now if Miss Hawkins can do it in
beauty, the rest of you can as well.

03:59.297 --> 04:02.929
Oh, how are we progressing with
the plans for our patriotic concert?

04:02.979 --> 04:07.972
Well, Chief, although we're still
looking for our top-of-the-bill
singer. Keep me informed.

04:08.022 --> 04:12.544
Thank you all very much.
Oh, Miss Mardle, one moment, please.

04:18.747 --> 04:21.658
How do you think Gordon's doing?
Oh, very well.

04:21.708 --> 04:25.061
Mm, I'm pleased with him too.
Let's return Miss Calthorpe to you

04:25.110 --> 04:29.583
in Accessories and see if he can
stand on his own two feet. Very good.
One more thing.

04:29.633 --> 04:33.794
I understand that you've become
a woman of independent means.

04:34.755 --> 04:38.467
Well, yes, I have,
but that doesn't change anything.

04:38.517 --> 04:42.149
I'm still very committed to the
store. I'm more committed to you.

04:42.199 --> 04:44.600
The store wouldn't be the same
without you.

04:45.360 --> 04:50.913
I just wanted to say enjoy it.
Enjoy what? Your money. Oh.

04:50.963 --> 04:54.275
Your brother left it to you
because he wanted you to have it.

04:54.324 --> 04:58.477
Don't feel guilty.
Have fun with it. You deserve to.

04:58.526 --> 05:00.528
Thank you, Mr Selfridge.

05:15.936 --> 05:18.937
You've been receiving visitors.

05:23.059 --> 05:28.131
A young man involved with one of
my charities - This is not what
we talked about, Mae.

05:28.181 --> 05:32.573
I thought you understood.
I am now a man of standing.

05:32.623 --> 05:36.105
Nobody lays with my wife but me.

05:37.585 --> 05:39.587
Oh.

05:43.949 --> 05:46.140
Loxley, give that back to me.

05:46.190 --> 05:50.032
It is a man's right, by law,
to enter his wife's bedroom.

05:51.273 --> 05:53.313
You won't be requiring this anymore.

06:09.802 --> 06:12.993
Excuse me? Do you have
an appointment to see Mr Selfridge?

06:13.043 --> 06:15.045
He'll see me.

06:15.604 --> 06:18.796
Mr Selfridge, good morning.
Bill Summertime.

06:18.847 --> 06:23.008
We met at Miss Day's card party.
I work for His Majesty's Government.

06:23.728 --> 06:26.130
Oh. Have a seat, please.

06:29.131 --> 06:31.403
Did Lord Edgerton send you?

06:31.452 --> 06:33.453
I have nothing to do with Edgerton.

06:34.974 --> 06:38.535
No, I procure something
entirely different.

06:41.817 --> 06:43.498
Information.

06:44.578 --> 06:47.050
What do you mean?
Intelligence gathering.

06:47.100 --> 06:51.332
It's vital to the war effort
that we know what the enemy's up to.

06:51.382 --> 06:54.974
You're winding down your supplies
in Germany, aren't you? Yes.

06:55.024 --> 06:58.136
It would be a good time for
you to take a little...

06:58.185 --> 07:00.416
business trip over there.

07:00.466 --> 07:03.508
There are persons of interest
we'd like you to contact.

07:04.468 --> 07:08.260
But... How would a trip to Germany
come across to the British public?

07:08.310 --> 07:10.501
I have a reputation to maintain.

07:10.551 --> 07:12.872
And we have
the resources to keep it quiet.

07:19.596 --> 07:21.597
Nobody need know.

07:24.158 --> 07:26.469
I don't know.

07:26.519 --> 07:28.520
You could be of great help to us.

07:38.706 --> 07:41.817
You rub it into your eyelashes
and it makes them lovely.

07:41.867 --> 07:44.979
Sorry I couldn't see you last night.
I was busy with this.

07:45.029 --> 07:49.860
It's a piece about your chief.
I hope he likes it. Oh, I'm sure
he will - cos you wrote it.

07:49.911 --> 07:52.952
The lady flatters me.
What does she want? Dinner. Done.

07:54.793 --> 07:56.794
Good luck.
Mmm.

07:56.914 --> 07:59.315
You and Mr Edward seem close,
Miss Hawkins.

08:00.556 --> 08:02.557
We enjoy spending time together.

08:04.078 --> 08:06.799
He is older than you
and has a certain reputation.

08:08.760 --> 08:10.761
I can look after myself, thank you.

08:12.122 --> 08:15.043
And unlike you,
I enjoy a gentleman's company.

08:19.325 --> 08:22.957
If there's a promotion on British
linen we should make the most of it.

08:23.007 --> 08:25.158
But why do we need
quite so many sheets?

08:25.208 --> 08:28.440
So we don't run out, of course,
even if everybody else does.

08:28.490 --> 08:31.801
What about the soap? You'd be
surprised how quickly it goes.

08:31.851 --> 08:35.763
All 25 boxes of it? Morning,
Mrs Crabb, how are you today?

08:35.813 --> 08:38.014
I need hairpins, Miss Mardle.
12 dozen.

08:38.855 --> 08:40.215
12...

08:46.258 --> 08:48.249
This is made out of British cloth.

08:48.300 --> 08:51.211
We had it in our warehouse,
so I suggested Mr Thackeray

08:51.261 --> 08:54.212
would use it for these patterns.
Mmm. Excellent.

08:54.262 --> 08:57.534
Very good, Mr Leclair.
Very good, both of you.

08:57.584 --> 08:59.585
Fashion has found its feet again.

09:01.346 --> 09:04.337
Mr Selfridge.
Ah, Mr Edwards. Here you are.

09:04.387 --> 09:06.988
Good morning.
Morning. Excuse me, gentlemen?

09:15.513 --> 09:17.263
Well, what is it?

09:17.313 --> 09:20.515
Don't you think you should
stop promoting German labels?

09:21.635 --> 09:25.388
What are you talking about? The hat
you wore into work this morning,

09:25.437 --> 09:28.509
it's a Homburg.

09:28.560 --> 09:31.350
The Homburg has been renamed,
Mr Thackeray.

09:31.401 --> 09:34.912
It's called the Biarritz now.
And those shoes,

09:34.963 --> 09:40.315
handmade in Munich. And I'll
continue to wear them because
they're extremely comfortable.

09:40.364 --> 09:43.717
Now, if you've finished, you need
to re-dress this mannequin.

09:43.767 --> 09:45.757
You've got the look entirely wrong.

09:45.808 --> 09:48.609
The skirt should be higher on
the waist, like this.

09:53.011 --> 09:58.724
"Mr Selfridge stated the Americans
shouldn't be trading with both sides,
making profit from war."

09:58.774 --> 10:02.326
I pinned your colours to the mast.
Thank you. This is good.

10:02.376 --> 10:06.848
You might lose a few friends.
Most of them have gone back to
the States anyway. Hm.

10:06.898 --> 10:11.610
I wanna write a piece about
the Procurement Committee.
They're a pretty powerful bunch.

10:11.661 --> 10:16.052
Don't talk to me about them.
I'm done with the lot of 'em.
Knocked you back, did they?

10:16.103 --> 10:19.024
I gave Loxley some contacts -
but I don't like him.

10:19.904 --> 10:23.016
Anyway, I'm not interested in
the Procurement Committee.

10:23.066 --> 10:25.467
There are other ways
to help the war effort.

10:28.829 --> 10:31.790
Delphine, come and look
what's just arrived.

10:35.752 --> 10:39.344
Don't take it.
Harry Selfridge is buying you.

10:39.394 --> 10:42.585
Let him. I've had enough
independence for one lifetime.

10:42.635 --> 10:44.957
Anyway, I'm not 20 anymore.

10:45.717 --> 10:48.308
You're as good as.
Oh, you're sweet, Jim,

10:48.359 --> 10:52.430
but I have to be realistic.
Now Mr Selfridge is quite a catch.

10:52.480 --> 10:55.592
He's the kind of man, the less you
ask for, the more he gives.

10:55.642 --> 10:58.313
He's married to your chum.
He makes her unhappy.

10:58.363 --> 11:01.194
She doesn't understand him.
And you do?

11:01.244 --> 11:04.486
Oh, yes. I know what makes
Harry Selfridge tick.

11:11.290 --> 11:13.320
Am I disturbing you?
No. Come on in.

11:13.371 --> 11:17.693
I'm just getting a waistcoat made
of this British cloth that
we're promoting.

11:18.654 --> 11:20.965
I just wanted to
say thank you for the wine,

11:21.015 --> 11:23.726
and to tell you
that I can't accept it.

11:23.775 --> 11:26.366
Of course you can.
You'd be doing me a favour.

11:26.417 --> 11:30.729
I need the space in my warehouse and
you organised a great evening
of cards.

11:30.779 --> 11:33.300
Even though you got
no joy from Lord Edgerton.

11:34.260 --> 11:37.572
Can you turn that around fast?
Thank you. Yes, sir.

11:37.623 --> 11:40.253
But Bill Summertime came to see me.

11:40.303 --> 11:42.055
Bill?

11:42.105 --> 11:44.536
But he hardly spoke to you
all evening.

11:44.586 --> 11:46.586
I don't know if
you know what he does.

11:47.387 --> 11:49.388
He enlightened me.

11:50.469 --> 11:52.620
Is he for real?
Well, yes.

11:52.670 --> 11:55.141
He's a very old friend,
we go way back.

11:55.191 --> 11:58.673
But he's impossible to say no to.
What did he come to see you about?

12:00.633 --> 12:02.635
Thank you, Miss Plunkett.

12:06.197 --> 12:08.198
I can't really discuss it.

12:11.079 --> 12:16.392
Huh. Don't be rash. I know you worry
you're not doing your bit for this
country - but it's not true.

12:16.442 --> 12:19.473
People come to this store
and their hearts lighten.

12:19.523 --> 12:22.754
They forget about their problems.
Believe me, I know.

12:22.804 --> 12:25.996
Is the club in trouble?
No.

12:26.046 --> 12:27.997
Only with supplies.

12:28.047 --> 12:31.288
These are tough times.
If there's anything else I can do...

12:32.369 --> 12:34.370
You're sweet.

12:35.730 --> 12:38.082
But I can look after myself.

12:38.132 --> 12:40.133
You should do the same.

12:51.699 --> 12:55.410
Rose. Delphine.
I haven't seen you in so long.

12:55.461 --> 12:59.133
You never come and see me at the
club anymore. I have been so busy

12:59.182 --> 13:01.454
with the store.
Oh, more charity events?

13:01.504 --> 13:03.494
Actually, I'm helping Harry,

13:03.544 --> 13:05.855
particularly with
the new female staff.

13:05.905 --> 13:07.936
Well, that's marvellous.
Hmm.

13:07.986 --> 13:10.258
He enjoyed his card evening
with you.

13:10.308 --> 13:14.740
I should've asked you before leading
him astray. Oh, I'm not his keeper.

13:14.790 --> 13:17.342
So am I forgiven, then?
Nothing to forgive.

13:17.392 --> 13:19.392
Oh, good.

13:20.113 --> 13:22.114
Well, I must rush. Bye, darling.

13:31.318 --> 13:32.319
Come.

13:33.959 --> 13:35.961
Ah, Mr Thackeray.

13:39.882 --> 13:42.804
What can I do for you?
It's a delicate matter.

13:52.288 --> 13:55.840
It's about Monsieur Leclair.
What about him?

13:55.890 --> 13:58.521
I think we need to consider
the possibility

13:58.571 --> 14:00.563
that he's not what he seems.

14:00.613 --> 14:02.613
Huh! What on earth do you mean?

14:03.334 --> 14:05.405
He's behaving strangely.

14:05.455 --> 14:08.967
I saw him, here in this store,
exchange money with a man.

14:09.017 --> 14:12.208
And I know for a fact he's
trying to locate a German person.

14:12.258 --> 14:16.090
A German person? I also think
he's been to Germany recently.

14:16.140 --> 14:19.491
Well, that can't be right. Am I
the only person in the whole store

14:19.541 --> 14:24.934
who can see him for what he is?
He returned, out of the blue,
just before the war started.

14:24.985 --> 14:30.738
He looked unkempt, he refused to
engage in questions about what he'd
been doing for the past four years -

14:30.788 --> 14:33.028
He was in America.
So why did he come back?

14:34.749 --> 14:39.262
These questions have to be asked.
The papers tell us there are
spies everywhere,

14:39.311 --> 14:42.983
and we must be vigilant.
All right, thank you, Mr Thackeray.

14:43.033 --> 14:45.034
I'll look into it.

14:53.878 --> 14:57.560
In the meantime, please keep
your concerns to yourself.

14:58.801 --> 15:00.922
We don't want to
start rumours flying.

15:16.730 --> 15:18.731
Where are you going to?

15:19.571 --> 15:23.013
A variety show. With Mr Colleano.

15:26.455 --> 15:28.646
And what's wrong with that?

15:28.696 --> 15:30.696
You could do better.

15:33.778 --> 15:36.250
You know,
Victor's a good, honest man.

15:36.300 --> 15:38.300
Yeah, unlike me, you mean?

15:39.661 --> 15:46.344
People are saying things about you,
Henri. Oh. What are they saying?

15:47.585 --> 15:49.626
Well, that you're hiding something.

15:50.867 --> 15:52.977
This country's gone mad.

15:53.028 --> 15:55.749
Well, you are hiding something,
aren't you?

15:57.670 --> 15:59.670
Why won't you talk to me?

16:00.552 --> 16:03.433
You, of all people, to doubt me.

16:05.674 --> 16:07.674
I don't want to.

16:08.635 --> 16:10.637
But you're not the man
I used to know.

16:17.639 --> 16:21.922
Piccadilly Circus via Charing Cross
and Shaftesbury Avenue! - Ready?

16:22.963 --> 16:27.964
Piccadilly Circus via Charing Cross
Road and Shaftesbury Avenue!

16:29.325 --> 16:31.327
Walk on!

