morning, Miss Mardle? I am,
Miss Hawkins. I went out last night.

22:12.394 --> 22:15.585
Oh. With Miss Towler?
All girls together?

22:15.635 --> 22:19.587
With Miss Towler and two gentlemen.
I had a most enjoyable evening.

22:19.637 --> 22:21.638
Mm.

22:28.881 --> 22:31.553
Miss Calthorpe, now you're
back at Accessories,

22:31.603 --> 22:33.754
I expect to see Accessories'
standards.

22:33.804 --> 22:37.075
Be careful with the handkerchiefs.
No creasing. Thank you.

22:37.125 --> 22:39.127
Yes, Miss Mardle.

22:41.848 --> 22:46.361
Happy to be back, then?
I'd forgotten what an old battleaxe
Miss M is.

22:46.410 --> 22:48.881
I should've stayed on Tea.

22:48.931 --> 22:53.484
Oh, this is for you. Well, not for
you exactly. For your sister.

22:53.534 --> 22:55.535
Oh.

22:58.456 --> 23:01.408
British made.
My sisters loved their dolls.

23:01.458 --> 23:05.730
Rotten not to have many.
Oh, Ruth will love it.

23:05.780 --> 23:07.981
Oh, but you shouldn't have.
I wanted to.

23:11.623 --> 23:15.225
You're a gentleman - and a friend.
Thank you.

23:25.910 --> 23:29.822
If Mrs Crabb had more to do,
perhaps she'd worry less.

23:29.872 --> 23:34.103
What's she worrying about?
She's stockpiling
the most peculiar things.

23:34.154 --> 23:38.545
Last night I stubbed my toe on
a jar of marmalade - under the bed.

23:38.596 --> 23:40.987
Doris hardly seems to notice
we're at war

23:41.037 --> 23:44.669
she's so taken with the children.
Mr Grove, Mr Crabb, good morning.

23:44.718 --> 23:48.191
Good morning, Miss Mardle. Aren't you
looking well, Miss Mardle?

23:48.241 --> 23:53.033
I've noticed recently that while
we're all getting older,
you seem to be getting younger.

23:53.083 --> 23:55.555
Are you wearing a new scent,
Miss Mardle?

23:55.604 --> 23:57.605
Yes, I thought I might spoil myself.

23:58.566 --> 24:03.318
Are arrangements moving forward for
the charity concert, Mr Crabb?
Indeed they are.

24:03.368 --> 24:05.689
We've found our singer,
a tenor called...

24:07.009 --> 24:10.762
A contact of Lady Loxley's.
Richard Chapman.

24:10.811 --> 24:16.885
Oh. Well, if he needs accompaniment,
my Belgian lodger is a marvellous
violinist.

24:16.935 --> 24:18.935
How's she settling in?

24:19.616 --> 24:23.648
Quite well, thank you. That's a good
idea. Thank you, Mr Mardle.

24:23.698 --> 24:25.699
Please ask her.
Oh. Indeed.

24:43.148 --> 24:45.538
Miss Plunkett said
you wanted to see me?

24:45.589 --> 24:48.630
Yes. Please, sit down.

24:55.393 --> 24:59.145
The fact is, there's been some
gossip in the store about you.

24:59.195 --> 25:01.666
It's all nonsense, of course.

25:01.717 --> 25:05.118
Well, I need the requisite details
in order to extinguish it.

25:06.118 --> 25:10.191
So,... could you tell me precisely
what you've been doing

25:10.241 --> 25:12.562
since you left Selfridges
four years ago?

25:14.203 --> 25:16.514
I've been in America, as you know.

25:16.564 --> 25:18.875
Yes, but for the whole time?

25:18.925 --> 25:20.926
No, not exactly.

25:22.647 --> 25:24.798
Where were you then?

25:24.847 --> 25:26.849
Europe.

25:28.169 --> 25:30.171
Germany?

25:31.652 --> 25:33.733
Yes, Germany.

25:37.574 --> 25:41.126
Henri, I have no intention of
enquiring into your private life.

25:41.176 --> 25:44.887
Good. Because I have no intention
of telling you about it.

25:44.938 --> 25:46.929
But what I would say is

25:46.979 --> 25:50.130
that Mr Selfridge has placed
a great deal of trust in you,

25:50.180 --> 25:53.172
and if you are holding anything back,
anything at all,

25:53.222 --> 25:55.583
now would be the time to tell me.

26:02.067 --> 26:04.067
There's something I must tell you.

26:06.588 --> 26:08.779
I'm going to hand in my notice.

26:08.830 --> 26:12.341
The French government is accepting
all the men for the army.

26:12.391 --> 26:14.392
I wish to leave as soon as I can.

26:21.196 --> 26:24.147
I heard this morning.
The bank's gonna give me a loan

26:24.197 --> 26:27.719
so I can get the restaurant going
again. Oh, that's wonderful.

26:29.759 --> 26:31.761
I'm going to hand in my notice.

26:34.963 --> 26:36.963
Mr Selfridge will miss you.

26:38.924 --> 26:41.685
Will you?
Of course I will. You know I will.

26:48.449 --> 26:50.960
You could come and run
the restaurant with me.

26:51.010 --> 26:53.011
What?

26:54.972 --> 26:56.973
Marry me.

26:58.094 --> 27:03.607
But - Just hear me out, all right?
You need somebody. You think you're
fine on your own - but you're not.

27:03.657 --> 27:06.888
Every since George left
you've been sad, and I see that

27:06.938 --> 27:12.651
and it breaks my heart. I wanna wake
up besides you every morning and fall
asleep besides you every night,

27:12.701 --> 27:17.453
and I think you want that, too.
Victor - We could really make
something of this restaurant.

27:17.503 --> 27:20.214
When we have children,
they can help us as well.

27:20.265 --> 27:22.976
We'll be a proper family.
Life is about people

27:23.026 --> 27:26.377
when it comes down to it,
and nothing else. Victor - Please,

27:26.428 --> 27:31.780
don't say no before you've had a
chance to think it through at least.
If you let me get a word in,

27:31.831 --> 27:33.631
you'd hear what I've got to say.

27:36.472 --> 27:38.473
It's yes.

27:42.515 --> 27:44.517
- Really?
- Really.

27:53.801 --> 27:55.802
Thank you.

27:57.243 --> 28:00.594
So Mr Grove has agreed to
let you play at the charity concert.

28:00.644 --> 28:04.076
Now there will be suffrage ladies
there. Suffrage ladies?

28:04.126 --> 28:06.127
Er... The bossy ladies.
Oh.

28:07.127 --> 28:11.480
But one of the things they do is
organise theatre events at
the military camps.

28:11.530 --> 28:13.651
They might be
able to get you some work.

28:14.411 --> 28:16.362
You are always thinking about me.

28:16.412 --> 28:20.254
Well, it's quite nice to have
someone to think about.

28:25.177 --> 28:27.898
Oh, I'm sorry I'm late.
We hadn't started eating.

28:29.458 --> 28:31.410
Has something happened?

28:31.460 --> 28:34.411
Erm... Well... erm...

28:34.461 --> 28:37.532
I shouldn't tell you,
I promised I wouldn't

28:37.582 --> 28:40.454
and you mustn't breathe a word -
Mr Colleano?

28:40.504 --> 28:42.375
He proposed.

28:42.425 --> 28:44.426
Ohh!
And he gave me this.

28:45.386 --> 28:47.977
Oh, Agnes, congratulations.
Thank you.

28:52.870 --> 28:54.821
So, to what do I owe the pleasure?

28:54.871 --> 28:57.232
Felt.
Felt?

28:58.232 --> 29:00.344
Yes, to line military coats.

29:00.394 --> 29:02.745
I need a great deal of it -
and quickly.

29:02.795 --> 29:04.795
I trust you have suppliers.
I do.

29:05.636 --> 29:08.748
Would this information be for
the Procurement Committee?

29:08.798 --> 29:11.229
Does it matter who it's for?
A great deal.

29:11.279 --> 29:17.552
There are businessmen in London who
are trying to buy up material to sell
to the enemy. American businessmen.

29:17.602 --> 29:22.404
Just because they're my countrymen
doesn't mean I have any intention
of helping them.

29:24.445 --> 29:26.446
How do you know about them anyway?

29:29.768 --> 29:32.890
What's so amusing?
Your hypocrisy.

29:33.730 --> 29:37.682
Until a couple of weeks ago, this
shop was full of German merchandise.

29:37.732 --> 29:42.044
As was every store in London.
Britain depended too much
on German manufacturing.

29:42.094 --> 29:44.295
But you still kept on buying
from the...

29:45.696 --> 29:47.697
..good old Fatherland.

29:49.337 --> 29:51.649
I don't trust you, Loxley,

29:51.698 --> 29:53.970
it's as simple as that.

29:54.020 --> 29:56.941
I can't and won't help you.
Find your felt elsewhere.

30:07.387 --> 30:09.978
Who are you to talk about trust,
Selfridge?

30:10.028 --> 30:13.589
You're a tradesman,
and trade is a dirty business.

30:14.550 --> 30:19.622
All you've done is build your vulgar
shop here and get rich.

30:19.672 --> 30:22.474
You've done absolutely nothing
for this country.

30:36.201 --> 30:38.432
There's a guest to see you,
Mr Selfridge.

30:38.481 --> 30:40.482
He's waiting in the courtyard.

30:41.843 --> 30:43.845
Thank you.

30:50.567 --> 30:52.998
Mr Summertime. Good evening.

30:53.048 --> 30:55.050
Mr Selfridge.

30:56.370 --> 30:58.372
We need to know your answer.

31:00.973 --> 31:03.483
Well, I made a fuss about
the government

31:03.534 --> 31:05.525
not using me for the war effort.

31:05.575 --> 31:07.896
I'd be a coward and a hypocrite
if I said no.

31:09.377 --> 31:12.848
Good man. Now, here's the names of
the manufacturers

31:12.899 --> 31:14.900
we wanted to try to meet.

31:16.820 --> 31:20.292
The name at the top is of
particular interest to us.

31:20.342 --> 31:23.533
He's due in Berlin
in the next couple of weeks, so...

31:23.583 --> 31:25.905
we maybe ask you to go
at a moment's notice.

31:32.748 --> 31:35.820
I was thinking about
going to Europe. Why?

31:35.870 --> 31:40.462
I have to tie up
some supply situations.

31:40.512 --> 31:43.223
But don't worry,
I'll be on American papers.

31:43.273 --> 31:45.985
I'll be fine.

31:46.035 --> 31:48.666
Where in Europe?
Paris mostly.

31:48.716 --> 31:50.717
Mmm.

32:07.506 --> 32:13.658
I'm excited about tonight. I need to
talk to you about something. If it's
about work, it can wait. It can't.

32:13.708 --> 32:15.939
You look beautiful.
Thanks.

32:15.989 --> 32:18.430
Oh, I'm looking forward to this.
Shall we go?

32:31.597 --> 32:33.598
Here, allow me.

32:35.960 --> 32:38.551
It's kind of you
to borrow these for me.

32:38.600 --> 32:40.642
You need to look your best,
don't you?

32:43.322 --> 32:45.484
Am I good?
Very good.

32:50.526 --> 32:55.319
Er... I thought you
might like to wear these.

32:55.368 --> 32:57.560
They belong to George.

32:57.609 --> 33:00.332
Are you sure?
He'd want for you to wear them.

33:09.096 --> 33:11.096
Good evening.
Good evening.

33:12.217 --> 33:14.338
Good evening, Mr Grove.
Good evening.

33:15.539 --> 33:17.539
Ah, Miss Towler.

33:18.260 --> 33:19.891
Good evening, Miss Mardle.

33:19.941 --> 33:24.213
Where is your violinist? Mr Chapman
would very much like to meet her.

33:24.263 --> 33:26.945
Oh, this is Florian, Mr Grove.
Ah.

33:28.906 --> 33:30.896
But... I thought...?

33:30.946 --> 33:35.299
Yes, there was a bit of mix-up, but
we're happy to have Florian staying
with us.

33:35.348 --> 33:37.699
Where is Mr Chapman?

33:37.749 --> 33:40.391
He's on the terrace,
waiting to begin.

33:41.352 --> 33:43.593
Just through there, Florian.
Thank you.

33:45.633 --> 33:47.635
Good luck.

33:49.876 --> 33:51.866
I can't quite believe you have

33:51.916 --> 33:54.668
a young man living with you
in your house.

33:54.718 --> 33:57.629
Well, I couldn't turn him away,
could I?

33:57.679 --> 34:01.481
Special times call for special
measures. Don't you think, Mr Grove?

34:02.402 --> 34:05.273
Now, if you'll excuse me?
Where am I sitting?

34:05.323 --> 34:07.364
Right this way, ma'am.
Oh, thank you.

34:10.646 --> 34:14.678
Good evening, Mr Selfridge.
Mrs Selfridge.
You look very smart, Mr Crabb.

34:14.728 --> 34:18.958
Oh. Could I have a quick
word, Chief? I'll see you in there.

34:19.009 --> 34:23.012
There's a gentleman to see you in
your office. He says it's urgent.

34:28.054 --> 34:30.565
Do you know what? Piccadilly.

34:30.616 --> 34:33.737
Good evening, Miss Towler.
Good evening, Mr Thackeray.

34:51.105 --> 34:53.176
Good evening, Mrs Selfridge.

34:53.226 --> 34:55.217
Lord Loxley. Lady Mae.

34:55.268 --> 34:57.339
I'm looking forward to this.

34:57.388 --> 35:00.900
A patriotic concert organised by
the only Americans left in town.

35:00.950 --> 35:04.982
We may be Americans, Lord Loxley,
but Selfridges is a British store

35:05.032 --> 35:07.863
and its very proud to play its part.
Where is Harry?

35:07.914 --> 35:10.915
He should be here any moment.
Please, take your seats.

35:12.036 --> 35:14.036
Mr Crabb, can I have a word?

35:15.157 --> 35:17.269
Um...
We really can't wait any longer.

35:17.318 --> 35:19.959
We'll have to begin without him.
Yes. Thank you.

35:21.320 --> 35:23.952
Gentlemen, we're about to start.
Thank you.

35:24.001 --> 35:26.433
We have to leave now, Mr Selfridge.

35:26.482 --> 35:28.674
T-Tonight?
Yes, right away. We've heard

35:28.724 --> 35:33.316
the chap we want you to meet is in
Berlin. He may not stay long.
I have a concert to attend.

35:33.366 --> 35:36.998
My wife and guests are waiting. Write
a note to your wife explaining.

35:37.048 --> 35:41.040
Say you need to
be in Paris straightaway.
An important supplier's in town.

35:41.090 --> 35:44.612
Ask her to explain to your employees
you'll be back in a few days.

35:45.332 --> 35:48.883
We want to reassure her,
and your staff.

35:48.934 --> 35:51.055
We don't want them
worrying about you.

35:57.858 --> 36:02.571
♪ And nations to Eastward,
and nations to Westward

36:02.621 --> 36:07.212
♪ As foemen may curse them,
the yeomen of England

36:07.262 --> 36:09.374
♪ No other land can nurse them

36:09.424 --> 36:12.895
♪ But their Motherland, old England!

36:12.946 --> 36:15.667
♪ And on her broad bosom -
Is everything all right?

36:16.628 --> 36:21.259
(It's Harry. He's going away. Can
you find out what's going on? Yeah.
Thank you.)

36:21.310 --> 36:27.072
♪..ever thrive! ♪

36:38.838 --> 36:42.350
Thank you. This next song is for
our boys at the front,

36:42.400 --> 36:44.751
but I need a little help
with this one,

36:44.801 --> 36:48.433
so which one of you lovely ladies
would like to join me?

36:48.483 --> 36:50.484
I will.

37:07.493 --> 37:12.165
♪ Up to mighty London
came an Irish man one day

37:12.215 --> 37:16.767
♪ As the streets were paved with
gold, sure everyone was gay

37:16.817 --> 37:21.729
♪ Singing songs of Piccadilly,
Strand, and Leicester Square

37:21.780 --> 37:28.413
♪ Till Paddy got excited,
then he shouted to them there...

37:28.463 --> 37:30.463
Please join in.
I'm sure you know it.

37:31.764 --> 37:36.016
♪ It's a long way to Tipperary

37:36.067 --> 37:40.818
♪ It's a long way to go

37:40.869 --> 37:45.621
♪ It's a long way to Tipperary

37:45.671 --> 37:51.344
♪ To the sweetest girl I know

37:51.394 --> 37:55.786
♪ Goodbye, Piccadilly

37:55.836 --> 37:59.838
♪ Farewell, Leicester Square

38:00.839 --> 38:05.951
♪ It's a long, long way to Tipperary

38:06.001 --> 38:09.563
♪ But my heart's right there...

38:16.486 --> 38:19.087
I'm late for your concert.
I'm so sorry, Harry.

38:20.608 --> 38:23.080
Bill.
Good evening, Delphine.

38:23.130 --> 38:27.522
Where are you going? I hope you're
not involving Harry in anything
dangerous?

38:27.572 --> 38:30.763
This has nothing to do with you.
I'm off on a business trip,

38:30.813 --> 38:33.685
that's all.
Please, don't worry Rose about this.

38:33.735 --> 38:37.456
She doesn't know.
I won't breathe a word to anyone.

38:38.777 --> 38:41.329
I'll be thinking of you.

38:41.378 --> 38:43.379
Good luck, Harry.

38:46.220 --> 38:48.222
We have to go, Mr Selfridge.

39:00.068 --> 39:03.980
♪ It's a long, long way to Tipperary

39:04.030 --> 39:09.112
♪ But my heart lies there! ♪

39:14.314 --> 39:17.426
Thank you, Mr Richard Chapman
and our surprise soloist,

39:17.476 --> 39:19.477
the lovely Lady Loxley.

39:23.639 --> 39:28.271
All the money raised tonight goes
towards provisions for our soldiers
at the front,

39:28.321 --> 39:31.442
and this next song is for them too.
Thank you.

39:40.367 --> 39:43.718
Did you find him?
No. He must have already left.

39:43.769 --> 39:45.770
Oh.

39:51.533 --> 39:54.054
♪ Oh, Danny Boy

39:54.694 --> 39:58.776
♪ The pipes, the pipes are calling

39:59.937 --> 40:03.528
♪ From glen to glen

40:03.578 --> 40:08.260
♪ And down the mountain side

40:09.341 --> 40:13.174
♪ The summer's gone

40:13.224 --> 40:17.335
♪ And all the flowers are dying -
Can I help you?

40:17.386 --> 40:20.617
Mrs Selfridge, I'm looking for
an Henri Leclair?

40:20.667 --> 40:22.378
(Henri?)
♪ 'Tis you must go -

40:22.427 --> 40:24.259
Come with me please, sir?

40:24.309 --> 40:26.310
♪ And I must bide

40:27.830 --> 40:31.502
♪ But come ye back

40:31.553 --> 40:34.864
♪ When summer's -
You're suspected of spying. What?

40:34.914 --> 40:38.706
Henri! Don't touch me.
What's this about? Henri!

40:38.756 --> 40:42.988
Hey, don't touch me! Excuse me.
There must be some sort of mistake.

40:43.038 --> 40:45.559
Stay back, miss.
All right, all right. Henri.

40:46.159 --> 40:49.752
♪ For I'll be there

40:49.802 --> 40:54.563
♪ In sunshine or in shadow

40:55.764 --> 40:58.876
♪ Oh, Danny Boy

40:58.926 --> 41:04.358
♪ Oh, Danny Boy, I love you so

41:04.408 --> 41:09.081
♪ And if you come

41:09.131 --> 41:13.043
♪ When all the flowers are dying

41:13.093 --> 41:17.485
♪ And I am dead

41:17.535 --> 41:21.497
♪ As dead I well may be

41:23.298 --> 41:26.489
♪ You'll come and find

41:26.539 --> 41:30.501
♪ The place where I am lying

41:31.582 --> 41:35.133
♪ And kneel and say

41:35.183 --> 41:38.946
♪ An Ave there for me

41:40.586 --> 41:43.537
♪ And I shall hear

41:43.588 --> 41:48.660
♪ Though soft you tread above me

41:48.710 --> 41:51.982
♪ And all my dreams

41:52.032 --> 41:55.633
♪ Will warm and sweeter be

41:56.994 --> 42:01.506
♪ If you'll not fail

42:01.556 --> 42:06.358
♪ To tell me that you love me

42:07.439 --> 42:09.951
♪ I'll simply sleep

42:10.001 --> 42:16.564
♪ In peace until you come to me! ♪

